        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1381</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000Z</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000Z.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Convergence in norm">Convergence in norm</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In a normed vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X, ||\cdot ||)]]></fr:tex>, a sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_n\}]]></fr:tex> is said to converge in norm to an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } ||x_n - x|| = 0]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>This is also called strong convergence to distinguish it from other types of convergence such as <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Y.xml" addr="FA-000Y" title="Weak Convergence">weak convergence</fr:link> or <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0010.xml" addr="FA-0010" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Convergence in norm has the following properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>The limit is unique</fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y_n \to  y]]></fr:tex> in norm, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ax_n + by_n \to  ax + by]]></fr:tex> in norm for any scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y_n \to  y]]></fr:tex> in norm, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x_n|| \to  ||x||]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x_n - y_n|| \to  ||x - y||]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>In a complete normed space (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>), every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000X.xml" addr="FA-000X" title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link> converges in norm to some element of the space</fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1383</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-000Q</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-000Q.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Convergent">Convergent</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_n)]]></fr:tex> in a metric space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is said to converge to a point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x_n, x) < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In this case, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is called the limit of the sequence, and we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_n \to  x]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \to  \infty ]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } x_n = x]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In functional analysis, there are various notions of convergence depending on the space and the context, including <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Y.xml" addr="FA-000Y" title="Weak Convergence">weak convergence</fr:link>, <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000Z.xml" addr="FA-000Z" title="Convergence in norm">convergence in norm</fr:link>, and <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0010.xml" addr="FA-0010" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1385</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-001S</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-001S.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Uniform Convergence">Uniform Convergence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A sequence of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> defined on a common domain <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> is said to converge uniformly to a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> if for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[ε > 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N(ε)]]></fr:tex> (independent of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>) such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x) - f(x)| < ε]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex> and all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \geq  N(ε)]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>In other words, the rate of convergence is uniform across all points in the domain. This is stronger than <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0010.xml" addr="FA-0010" title="Pointwise Convergence">pointwise convergence</fr:link>, where the rate of convergence can vary from point to point.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Uniform convergence has several important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>If each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n]]></fr:tex> is continuous and the sequence converges uniformly to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is also continuous</fr:li>
<fr:li>If each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n]]></fr:tex> is integrable and the sequence converges uniformly to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n \to  \infty } \int _D f_n(x) dx = \int _D f(x) dx]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>If each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_n]]></fr:tex> is differentiable and the sequence of derivatives <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f'_n\}]]></fr:tex> converges uniformly, then the original sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> converges uniformly to a differentiable function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f'(x) = \lim _{n \to  \infty } f'_n(x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>A common criterion for uniform convergence is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001V.xml" addr="FA-001V" title="Weierstrass M-test">Weierstrass M-test</fr:link>, which states that if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_n\}]]></fr:tex> is a sequence of functions satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_n(x)| \leq  M_n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  D]]></fr:tex>, and if the series <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{n=1}^{\infty } M_n]]></fr:tex> converges, then the series <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _{n=1}^{\infty } f_n(x)]]></fr:tex> converges uniformly on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
